      for bandage","comment":null,"color":{"r":0.0,"g":0.0,"b":0.0,"a":1.0},"guid":"52224537-9e38-4cb4-a0e6-fb1743db8b91","$version":"A","$type":"Unity.VisualScripting.GraphGroup"},{"position":{"xMin":2065.0,"yMin":222.0,"xMax":2854.0,"yMax":652.0},"label":"remove
      item from list, set it to despawned state","comment":null,"color":{"r":0.0,"g":0.0,"b":0.0,"a":1.0},"guid":"d0cd4ad5-611c-4669-add4-4cf980217d55","$version":"A","$type":"Unity.VisualScripting.GraphGroup"},{"position":{"xMin":274.0,"yMin":1409.0,"xMax":562.0,"yMax":1661.0},"title":"Inventory
      logic notes","body":"Make UI reflect changes in the inventory - use arrays.\n1.
      first, check if there is an item. \n     if not, remove the sprite on that
      slot (if there was any). \n     if there is an item, get its tag, and based
      on that tag show the corresponding sprite.\n\n2. do this for every item in
      the array","colorTheme":"Classic","guid":"f9b34a43-4fac-48c2-9b37-82e3d75f1f82","$type":"Unity.VisualScripting.StickyNote"},{"position":{"xMin":1996.0,"yMin":764.0,"xMax":2328.0,"yMax":997.0},"title":"this
      might not work (it doesnt but this has been solved!","body":"the problem is
      because we using a list. i.e. the player has the bandage in the second slot
      (in the list it''s index 1). \nIf there are 3 items in the list, and we try
      using up this item, there are now 2 items in the list. \n\nThe order in which
      the inventory UI updates will always be in this order: update 3rd slot, update
      2nd slot, and lastly 1st slot.\nFunctionally, this means that each time the
      UI updates, it has to check which slots are empty. How? by getting the size
      of the list and just hard coding it. this would be much easier had arrays existed
      in visual scripting :/ ","colorTheme":"Classic","guid":"40f0bf99-d8b0-4075-8c1a-700a980201fb","$type":"Unity.VisualScripting.StickyNote"},{"position":{"xMin":242.0,"yMin":-612.0,"xMax":517.0,"yMax":-480.0},"title":"Sticky
      Note","body":"This could be a function... yeah... but like I don''t feel like
      working on this part anymore...","colorTheme":"Classic","guid":"d024d1c6-fccb-480a-88f1-df685324e849","$type":"Unity.VisualScripting.StickyNote"}],"$version":"A"}}'
